column2: How to find last index of item in linked list in java
column3:
I just started a data structures and algorithms class and was introduced to linked lists for the first time. I have a decent understanding of how they work in theory but am having a hard time working with them.

I am struggling with this homework assignment:

Write a method lastIndexOf that accepts an integer value as a parameter and that returns the index in the list of the last occurrence of that value, or -1 if the value is not found in the list. For example, if a variable list stores the following sequence of values, then the call of list.lastIndexOf(18) should return 6 because that is the index of the last occurrence of 18:

[1, 18, 2, 7, 18, 39, 18, 40] If the call had instead been list.lastIndexOf(3), the method would return -1 because 3 does not appear in the list. You may not call any other methods of the class to solve this problem.

Assume that you are adding this method to the LinkedIntList class as defined below:

public class LinkedIntList {
    private ListNode front;   // null for an empty list
    ...
}

Here is my code:

public int lastIndexOf(int value) {
    ListNode current = front;
    int target;
    while (current != null) {
      
    if(current.data == value) {
        target = current.data;
         return target;
    }
      current = current.next;
     
        
    }
    return -1;
}

Now the 2 issues I am facing are 1) that I am returning the actual value of the node and not its index, and 2) that I am only returning the first occurrence of that value and not the last.

I hope this isn't a stupid question and I appreciate your help.

column2: Is there a way to build an already-existing JavaFX app jar into a native application using GraalVM's Native Image?
column3:
Overview

I have a JavaFX application (a mix of pure Java and B4J) that is compiled with JDK 19 into a jar. I would like to be able to package this application into a native executable. GraalVM's Native Image seemed like a promising option. I succeeded with the CLI version of this app. However, with the JavaFX version, I can't get native-image to find the JavaFX modules and the build fails.

I am doing this on Windows but my eventual goal is to build executables for Windows and Linux. I've already succeeded in doing so for the CLI version of my app.

I am using GraalVM 22.3.1.

Details

Running the JavaFX app like this works:

java --module-path "%JAVA_HOME%\javafx\lib" --add-modules=javafx.controls,javafx.graphics,javafx.swing,javafx.web,javafx.fxml,javafx.swt --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control.inputmap=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.scene=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control.behavior=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.scene.traversal=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/javafx.scene=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.collections=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.event=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.css=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.runtime=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control.skin=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.geom=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/javafx.scene.canvas=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.geom.transform=ALL-UNNAMED -jar MyApp.jar

The GraalVM Native Image documentation suggests that I should be able to adapt the above command to run with native-image like so:

native-image --verbose --module-path "%MODULE_PATH%" --add-modules=javafx.controls,javafx.graphics,javafx.swing,javafx.web,javafx.fxml,javafx.swt --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control.inputmap=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.scene=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control.behavior=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.scene.traversal=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/javafx.scene=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.collections=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.event=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.css=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.runtime=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.controls/com.sun.javafx.scene.control.skin=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.geom=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/javafx.scene.canvas=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=javafx.graphics/com.sun.javafx.geom.transform=ALL-UNNAMED -jar MyApp.jar

I've tried this where MODULE_PATH=%JAVA_HOME%\javafx\lib and where MODULE_PATH equals a comma-separated list of the full path to all the contents (javafx.base.jar, etc...) of that directory. In both cases, native-image's verbose logs report that -imagemp contains the value of the MODULE_PATH. The verbose logs report -imagemp as distinct from -module-path leading me to believe the former is the module path for the image being generated and the latter is the module path for the JVM instance running native-image. However, for both values of MODULE_PATH, it aborts with

Error occurred during initialization of boot layer
java.lang.module.FindException: Module javafx.swt not found
Error: Image build request failed with exit status 1
com.oracle.svm.driver.NativeImage$NativeImageError: Image build request failed with exit status 1
        at org.graalvm.nativeimage.driver/com.oracle.svm.driver.NativeImage.showError(NativeImage.java:1730)
        at org.graalvm.nativeimage.driver/com.oracle.svm.driver.NativeImage.build(NativeImage.java:1427)
        at org.graalvm.nativeimage.driver/com.oracle.svm.driver.NativeImage.performBuild(NativeImage.java:1387)
        at org.graalvm.nativeimage.driver/com.oracle.svm.driver.NativeImage.main(NativeImage.java:1374)

I tried removing javafx.swt from the added modules. native-image then fails while mentioning its inability to find another javafx module, leading me to believe that native-image is not finding any of the javafx modules.

Is there a way to get this to work? Or an alternative?

  • I've looked at Gluon's GraalVM solution but their GraalVM download has JDK 17 in it. I need JDK 19. It also looks like it's designed for projects that are started from scratch, not for an already existing jar.
  • I've also looked at putting the module-path in the jar's MANIFEST.MF. However it seems only Class-Path is supported. And I'm not sure this would fix anything since native-image is correctly receiving the module path info from the command line. It's just not able to use it to find the javafx modules.

column2: Custom application error messages not working when using Waffle
column3:
I have Waffle in a Java Spring Boot application.

When I throw a custom error, such as the one below, Waffle gets in the middle and sends a different error message to the caller.

throw new ResponseStatusException(HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST);

That should return a 404 BAD REQUEST message to the caller.

But instead, it returns a 500 INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR.

At the IDE console it displays the following message when the custom error message is thrown:

Exception Processing ErrorPage[errorCode=0, location=/error] java.lang.RuntimeException: Invalid Authorization header: Negotiate

Here is the code.

@Configuration
@EnableWebSecurity
@EnableGlobalMethodSecurity(securedEnabled = true)
public class SecurityConfig extends WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter {
    
    @Autowired
    private NegotiateSecurityFilter negotiateSecurityFilter;

    @Autowired
    private NegotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint entryPoint;
    
    @Override
    protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        
          http
            .csrf().disable()
                .authorizeRequests()
                .anyRequest()
                .authenticated()
                .and()
                .httpBasic()
                .authenticationEntryPoint(entryPoint)
                .and()
                .addFilterBefore(negotiateSecurityFilter, BasicAuthenticationFilter.class)                
                .headers()
                .addHeaderWriter(new StaticHeadersWriter("Access-Control-Allow-Credentials", "true"));  
         
        http.cors();         
                
    }
    
    @Override
    @Autowired
    protected void configure(AuthenticationManagerBuilder auth) throws Exception {      
        auth.inMemoryAuthentication();
    }
    
}

@Configuration
public class WaffleConfig {
    
    @Bean
    public WindowsAuthProviderImpl waffleWindowsAuthProvider() {
        return new WindowsAuthProviderImpl();
    }

    @Bean
    public NegotiateSecurityFilterProvider negotiateSecurityFilterProvider(
            WindowsAuthProviderImpl windowsAuthProvider) {
        return new NegotiateSecurityFilterProvider(windowsAuthProvider);
    }

    @Bean
    public BasicSecurityFilterProvider basicSecurityFilterProvider(
            WindowsAuthProviderImpl windowsAuthProvider) {
        return new BasicSecurityFilterProvider(windowsAuthProvider);
    }

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterProviderCollection waffleSecurityFilterProviderCollection(
            NegotiateSecurityFilterProvider negotiateSecurityFilterProvider,
            BasicSecurityFilterProvider basicSecurityFilterProvider) {
        SecurityFilterProvider[] securityFilterProviders =
                {negotiateSecurityFilterProvider, basicSecurityFilterProvider};
        return new SecurityFilterProviderCollection(securityFilterProviders);
    }

    @Bean
    public NegotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint negotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint(
            SecurityFilterProviderCollection securityFilterProviderCollection) {
        NegotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint negotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint =
                new NegotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint();
        negotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint.setProvider(securityFilterProviderCollection);
        return negotiateSecurityFilterEntryPoint;
    }

    @Bean
    public NegotiateSecurityFilter waffleNegotiateSecurityFilter(
            SecurityFilterProviderCollection securityFilterProviderCollection) {
        NegotiateSecurityFilter negotiateSecurityFilter = new NegotiateSecurityFilter();
        negotiateSecurityFilter.setProvider(securityFilterProviderCollection);
        return negotiateSecurityFilter;
    }

    // This is required for Spring Boot so it does not register the same filter twice
    @Bean
    public FilterRegistrationBean waffleNegotiateSecurityFilterRegistration(
            NegotiateSecurityFilter waffleNegotiateSecurityFilter) {
        FilterRegistrationBean registrationBean = new FilterRegistrationBean();
        registrationBean.setFilter(waffleNegotiateSecurityFilter);
        registrationBean.setEnabled(false);
        return registrationBean;
    }

}

column2: Espresso Gives AmbiguousViewMatcher Exception, When Using first(Matcher), I Get NoMatchingViewException
column3:
I have a ViewInteraction Query:

allOf(withId(R.id.elementId), withText("text"))

When I try to query this view, I receive an AmbiguousViewMatcher exception. This is expected as this view is part of a ListView cell.

However, I only want the first result on the page anyway. So, I implemented the function found here: First Matcher Function

public static <T> Matcher<T> first(final Matcher<T> matcher) {
    return new BaseMatcher<T>() {
        boolean isFirst = true;

        @Override
        public boolean matches(final Object item) {
            if (isFirst && matcher.matches(item)) {
                isFirst = false;
                return true;
            }

            return false;
        }

        @Override
        public void describeTo(final Description description) {
            description.appendText("should return first matching item");
            matcher.describeTo(description);
        }
    };
}

When this function runs on the element, I get the following output:

androidx.test.espresso.NoMatchingViewException: No views in hierarchy found matching: should return first matching item(view.getId() is <2131362844/com.myapp:id/elementId> and an instance of android.widget.TextView and view.getText() with or without transformation to match: is "text")

And I'm querying it like so:

onView(first(allOf(withId(R.id.elementId), withText("text"))))

Does anyone have an idea of why I would go from 8 ambiguous views to no matching views according to this function? I've also added logs, and I'm seeing the view I want go through the function, but it's not detecting it as a match.

What's weirder is that a similar function to this (found here), was working just fine until a month or so ago. Suddenly, both of these functions stopped matching things for us.

column2: Beam Flatten receives input but no output
column3:
I have Beam / Dataflow streaming pipeline (unbounded stream from Pubsub) that diverges by filtering (plus some intermediate processing, windowing and grouping) and eventually converges using Flatten to write data in the DB.

The two PTransforms converging have the same output (PCollection<KV<String, GenericRecord>>). The problems are:

  1. merge_pipeline_branches PTransform starts grayed out when all other PTransforms are in green, and remains grayed out all throughout.
  2. No emitted output from the merge_pipeline_branches PTransform going to write_data, although it receives input. Admittedly, only the left upstream PTransform streams data into it; the right one does not generate data yet.

Here is the code snippet:

// Merge the two writable PCollections
PCollection<KV<String, GenericRecord>> toWrite1 = ...
PCollection<KV<String, GenericRecord>> toWrite2 = ...

PCollectionList<KV<String, GenericRecord>> collections = PCollectionList.of(toWrite1).and(toWrite2);

PCollection<KV<String, GenericRecord>> merged = collections
        .apply("merge_pipeline_branches", Flatten.<KV<String, GenericRecord>>pCollections())

merge.apply("write_data", ...);

I read the documentation for PCollectionList::and and it says: https://beam.apache.org/releases/javadoc/2.40.0/org/apache/beam/sdk/values/PCollectionList.html#and-org.apache.beam.sdk.values.PCollection-

Returns a new PCollectionList that has all the PCollections of this PCollectionList 
plus the given PCollection appended to the end.

Please clarify: Does this mean the merge_pipeline_branches waits for both the two upstream PTransforms to have data in order for it to start streaming the output?

If that is the case, that is not the behavior that I want to happen. I simply want to merge the streaming, not the data themselves. I want to funnel the outputs of the two upstream PTransforms into write_data continuously and independent of each other.

Am I using the correct class/method, which is Flatten.<T>pCollections()? Or should I use a different paradigm for achieving what I want?

column2: Start spring integration channel adapter and wait for the flow to complete
column3:
I have a spring boot application and have a requirement where I need to poll the database for some data and after receiving that data from db, poll another system for more data. I'm using spring integration and have defined the following components -

Channels:

  1. evenChannel
  2. controlChannel
  3. systemChannel
  4. taskStatusChannel (QueueChannel)
  5. discardChannel

Adapters and ServiceActivators:

    @Bean
    @InboundChannelAdapter(channel = "eventChannel", poller = @Poller(fixedDelay = "1000", taskExecutor = "executor"),
            autoStartup = "false")
    @EndpointId("jdbcPollingAdapter")
    public JdbcPollingChannelAdapter pollingChannelAdapter() {
        JdbcPollingChannelAdapter adapter = new JdbcPollingChannelAdapter(this.dataSource, SQL);
        adapter.setRowMapper((rs, index) -> new TestEvent(rs.getString("eventName"), rs.getString("eventStatus"),
                rs.getTimestamp("createdDate"), rs.getTimestamp("updatedDate")));

        return adapter;
    }

    @Bean
    @InboundChannelAdapter(channel = "graphQLChannel", poller = @Poller(fixedRate = "1000"), autoStartup = "false")
    @EndpointId("graphQLPollingAdapter")
    public GraphQLPollingService graphQLPollingService() {
        return new GraphQLPollingService();
    }

    @Bean
    @ServiceActivator(inputChannel = "controlChannel")
    public ExpressionControlBusFactoryBean controlBus() {
        return new ExpressionControlBusFactoryBean();
    }

Integration Flows:

    @Bean
    public IntegrationFlow flow1() {
        return IntegrationFlow.from(eventChannel)
                              .filter(eventFilter)
                              .handle(msg -> {
                                  trigger("@jdbcPollingAdapter.stop()");
                                  trigger("@graphQLPollingAdapter.start()");
                              })
                              .get();

    }

    private void trigger(String expression) {
        controlChannel.send(new GenericMessage<>(expression));
    }

    @Bean
    public IntegrationFlow discardFlow() {
        return IntegrationFlow.from(discardChannel)
                              .handle(msg -> log.info("Discarded msg: {}", msg))
                              .get();
    }

    @Bean
    public IntegrationFlow graphQLFlow() {
        return IntegrationFlow.from(graphQLChannel)
                              .filter(graphQLFilter)
                              .handle(msg -> {
                                  trigger("@graphQLPollingAdapter.stop()");
                                  taskStatusChannel.send(new GenericMessage<>("COMPLETED"));
                              })
                              .get();
    }

I start the JDBC polling adapter via a REST call but the call returns immediately. I want the call to wait for all the flows to complete and then return.

To summarize, I want something like this -

1. REST call to RestController 
2. RestController (start jdbc polling adapter and wait) 
3. when data received [1. stop jdbc polling adapter 2. start systemA polling adapter] 
4. when systemA data received [1. stop systemA polling adapter] 
5. RestController returns 200 OK

How can this be achieved? Thanks for your answer!

column2: Not able to connect to rabbitmq instance using Java

From my java program (which is not dockerized) I am trying to connect to the container listening on 5673 by using the amqp-client maven library. The code looks something like this:

ConnectionFactory factory = new ConnectionFactory();
Connection connection = factory.newConnection("amqp://guest:guest@localhost:5673");

Channel channel = connection.createChannel();
channel.queueDeclare("region", true, false, false, null);

DefaultConsumer consumer =
    new DefaultConsumer(channel) {

      @Override
      public void handleConsumeOk(String consumerTag) {
        super.handleConsumeOk(consumerTag);
      }

      @Override
      public void handleDelivery(
          String consumerTag, Envelope envelope, AMQP.BasicProperties properties, byte[] body)
          throws IOException {
        String message = new String(body, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
        log.info(message);
      }
    };

channel.queueBind("region", "gas_region", "");
channel.basicConsume("region", true, consumer);

The problem I have is that my Java program keeps connecting to the 5672 instance instead of the one listening on 5673. I noticed that because I see the created queue in the 5672 instance instead of the other one and also my program doesn't find the configured exchange in the 5673 instance. The docker compose configuration for my rabbitmq instances looks like this:

package cookbook;

import java.io.IOException;
import java.lang.ModuleLayer.Controller;
import java.net.URL;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.ResourceBundle;

import javafx.beans.value.ChangeListener;
import javafx.beans.value.ObservableValue;
import javafx.event.ActionEvent;
import javafx.fxml.FXML;
import javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader;
import javafx.fxml.Initializable;
import javafx.scene.control.ListView;
import javafx.scene.control.TextArea;
import javafx.scene.control.TextField;
import javafx.scene.input.KeyEvent;
import javafx.scene.layout.AnchorPane;
import javafx.scene.layout.TilePane;
import javafx.stage.Popup;

public class recipeAddController implements Initializable {

    @FXML
    private ListView<String> allTagField;

    @FXML
    private TextField customTagField;

    @FXML
    private TextArea descriptionField;

    @FXML
    private TextField nameField;

    @FXML
    private ListView<String> premadeTagField;

    @FXML
    private AnchorPane recipeAddPane;

    private ArrayList<String> premadeTags = new ArrayList<String>(
            Arrays.asList("vegetarian", "vegan", "lactose free", "gluten free", "starter", "main course",
                    "dessert", "sweets"));

    private ArrayList<String> CustomTags = new ArrayList<String>();

    private ArrayList<String> allTags = new ArrayList<String>();

    private Popup me;

    private TilePane listField;

    @Override
    public void initialize(URL location, ResourceBundle resources) {
        // Set premade tags
        premadeTagField.getItems().setAll(premadeTags.toArray(new String[0]));
        premadeTagField.getSelectionModel().selectedItemProperty().addListener(new ChangeListener<String>() {

            // What happens when you press a tag
            @Override
            public void changed(ObservableValue<? extends String> observable, String oldValue, String newValue) {
                String currentTag = premadeTagField.getSelectionModel().getSelectedItem();
                premadeTags.remove(currentTag);
                premadeTagField.getItems().remove(currentTag);
                addTag(currentTag);
            }
        });
    }

    public void init(Popup me, TilePane listField) {
        this.me = me;
        this.listField = listField;
    }

    @FXML
    void EnterCustomTag(KeyEvent event) {
        if (event.getCode() == event.getCode().ENTER && customTagField.getText() != "") {
            String tag = customTagField.getText();
            CustomTags.add(tag);
            addTag(tag);
            customTagField.setText("");
        }
    }

    @FXML
    void addRecipe(ActionEvent event) throws IOException {
        FXMLLoader loader = new FXMLLoader();
        loader.setLocation(getClass().getResource("/Recipe.fxml"));
        AnchorPane page = (AnchorPane) loader.load();
        recipeController controller = loader.getController();

        String recipeName = nameField.getText();
        String description = descriptionField.getText();
        String[] tags = allTags.toArray(new String[0]);

        controller.setRcipe(new Recipe(recipeName, description, tags));
        listField.getChildren().add(page);
        cancelRecipeCreation(null);
    }

    @FXML
    void cancelRecipeCreation(ActionEvent event) {
        me.hide();
    }

    private void addTag(String tag) {
        allTags.add(tag);
        allTagField.getItems().add(0, tag);
    }

}

column2: Java thread wait and notify not working properly?
column3:
I have an application where I implemented myself a connection pool as singleton. Basically, it has a LinkedList availableConnections where I keep the available connections.

    private volatile LinkedList<SocketAdapter> availableConnections = new LinkedList<>();

I have methods getConnection and returnConnection.

The problem is when I try to get the connection (from a request thread), I synchronize the list availableConnections and check if it's empty. If so, I do availableConnections.wait().

    public SocketAdapter getConnection() throws InterruptedException {
        synchronized (availableConnections) {
            while (availableConnections.isEmpty()) {
                availableConnections.wait();
            }
            return availableConnections.removeFirst();
        }
    }

When the connection is finished using try -> finally, I return the connection

    public void returnConnection(SocketAdapter socket) {
        synchronized (availableConnections) {
            availableConnections.add(socket);
            availableConnections.notify();
        }
    }

The problem is when the wait wakes up, sometimes the list is empty:

1 - 14:27:44.593484500 - [Thread6] - *MFConnection - Getting socket 1 - availableConnections: 0
2 - 14:27:44.802258800 - [Thread6] - *MFConnection - END - returnConnection socket1
3 - 14:27:44.802258800 - [Thread6] - returnSyncConnection - availableConnections.notify() - Returning socket 1
4 - 14:27:44.802258800 - [Thread6] - *MFConnection - START - Sync getConnection()
5 - 14:27:44.802258800 - [Thread6] - *MFConnection - Getting socket 1 - availableConnections: 0
6 - 14:27:44.802258800 - [Thread0] - *MFConnection - isEmpty() - wait() - AWAKE - availableConnections: 0
7 - 14:27:44.802258800 - [Thread0] - *** EMPTY
8 - 14:27:44.802258800 - [Thread0] - *MFConnection - isEmpty() - wait()
...
9 - 14:27:45.578528600 - [Thread0] - *MFConnection - isEmpty() - wait() - AWAKE - availableConnections: 1
10 - 14:27:45.579679600 - [Thread0] - *MFConnection - Getting socket 2 - availableConnections: 0

We can see on log line 3, Thread6 returned the connection on availableConnections and called notify(). Right after, this same Thread6 was able to get connection on line 4 and 5.

On line 6, the other Thread0 (that was notified, i suppose) wakes up but see an empty list and get's back to wait().

This Thread0 wakes up (this time) after 1 second, on line 9.

Sometimes in my test it takes 10 seconds and I'm holding a request for that time until some notify() activate this thread back.

Any thoughts on this?

I didn't use volatile at first but than I added.

I'm expecting the thread follow the wait order and just wakes up then there's a connection available, that should happen right after someone return the connection.

The thread that returns the connection, looks like it has priority, what is bad for what I'm expecting. If it happens, it will not follow the getConnection priority order.

column2: My Chess AI performs wrong moves (MCTS algorithm)
column3:
I tried to implement the mcts algorithm in my chess game and it's not working, the AI perform the samne moves each time and not actuilly thinking. the classes I crerated are: Node,State,MCTS,UCT. I would really really appriciate if someone can take a look because it's due tommorow. I just need to know if I implemented it right.

this is the MCTS class: `

package AI;

import Model.*;
import Tree.Node;
import Tree.Tree;

import java.util.List;

public class MonteCarloTreeSearch {
        private static final int WIN_SCORE = 1000;

        private ChessPieceColor color;

        private int level;

        private boolean isWhiteTurn;

        public MonteCarloTreeSearch() {
            this.level = 3;
        }

        public int getLevel() {
            return level;
        }

        public void setLevel(int level) {
            this.level = level;
        }

        private int getMillisForCurrentLevel() {
            return 2 * (this.level - 1) + 1;
        }

        public Board findNextMove(GameModel model, boolean isWhiteTurn) {
            long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
            long end = start + 60L * getMillisForCurrentLevel();
             this.color = isWhiteTurn ? ChessPieceColor.WHITE : ChessPieceColor.BLACK;
            Node tree = new Node();
            tree.getState().setModel(model);
            while (System.currentTimeMillis() < end) {


                // Phase 1 - Selection
                Node promisingNode = selectPromisingNode(tree);


                // Phase 2 - Expansion
                // check if the chosen state is a game in progress
                // if so expand the tree
                if (promisingNode.getState().getModel().checkStatus(promisingNode.getState().getBoard(),color).equals(GameStatus.IN_PROGRESS))
                    expandNode(promisingNode);



                // Phase 3 - Simulation
                Node nodeToExplore = promisingNode;
                if (promisingNode.getChildArray().size() > 0) {
                    nodeToExplore = promisingNode.getRandomChildNode();
                }
                GameStatus simulationResult = simulateRandomPlayout(nodeToExplore);
                //System.out.println("phase 3 simulation");

                // Phase 4 - Update
                backPropogation(nodeToExplore, simulationResult);
                //System.out.println("phase 4 backPropogation");
            }

            Node winnerNode = tree.getChildWithMaxScore();
            return winnerNode.getState().getModel().getChessBoard();
        }

        private Node selectPromisingNode(Node tree) {
            Node node = tree;
            while (node.getChildArray().size() != 0) {
                node = UCT.findBestNodeWithUCT(node);
            }
            return node;
        }

        private void expandNode(Node node) {
            List<State> possibleStates = node.getState().getAllPossibleStates();
            possibleStates.forEach(state -> {
                Node newNode = new Node(state);
                newNode.setParent(node);
                newNode.getState().switchPlayer();
                node.getChildArray().add(newNode);
            });
        }

        private void backPropogation(Node nodeToExplore, GameStatus simulationResult) {
            Node tempNode = nodeToExplore;
            while (tempNode != null) {
                tempNode.getState().incrementVisit();
                // get the desired status for the current player
                GameStatus desiredStatus = tempNode.getState().getIsWhiteTurn() ? GameStatus.WHITE_WINS : GameStatus.BLACK_WINS;
                if (desiredStatus.equals(simulationResult))
                    tempNode.getState().addScore(WIN_SCORE);

                tempNode = tempNode.getParent();
            }
        }

        // simulate the game until checkmate
        private GameStatus simulateRandomPlayout(Node node) {
            Node tempNode = new Node(node);
            State tempState = tempNode.getState();
            // get the state's status
            GameStatus boardStatus = tempState.getModel().checkStatus(tempState.getBoard(),color);
            // get the desired status for the opponent
            GameStatus op = tempState.getOpponent().equals(ChessPieceColor.WHITE) ? GameStatus.WHITE_WINS : GameStatus.BLACK_WINS;
            // if the opponent wins set a min win score
            if (boardStatus.equals(op)) {
                tempNode.getParent().getState().setWinScore(Integer.MIN_VALUE);
                return boardStatus;
            }

            // game still in progress so keep simulating
            tempNode.getState().getModel().setNumOfMoves(0);
            while (boardStatus.equals(GameStatus.IN_PROGRESS)) {
                // simulate the next move
                tempState.randomPlay();
                tempState.getModel().increaseMoves();
                tempState.getModel().switchTurn();
                // update the board status
                boardStatus = tempState.getModel().checkStatus(tempState.getBoard(),color);
            }
            System.out.println(boardStatus);
            return boardStatus;
        }

    }

this is the State class:

package AI;

import Model.*;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.Comparator;
import java.util.List;

public class State {
    private GameModel model;
    private boolean isWhiteTurn;
    private int visitCount;
    private double winScore;

    public State() {
        this.model = new GameModel();
    }

    public State(State state) {
        this.model = new GameModel(state.getBoard());
        this.isWhiteTurn = state.getIsWhiteTurn();
        this.visitCount = state.getVisitCount();
        this.winScore = state.getWinScore();
    }

    public State(GameModel model) {

    }

    GameModel getModel() {
        return this.model;
    }

    Board getBoard() {

    }

    void setModel(GameModel model) {
        this.model = model;
    }

    boolean getIsWhiteTurn() {
        return this.isWhiteTurn;
    }

    void setIsWhiteTurn(boolean is) {
        this.isWhiteTurn = is;
    }

    ChessPieceColor getOpponent() {
        return isWhiteTurn ? ChessPieceColor.BLACK : ChessPieceColor.WHITE;
    }

    public int getVisitCount() {
        return visitCount;
    }

    public void setVisitCount(int visitCount) {
        this.visitCount = visitCount;
    }

    double getWinScore() {
        return winScore;
    }

    void setWinScore(double winScore) {
        this.winScore = winScore;
    }

    // get all possible states based on all current possible moves
    public List<State> getAllPossibleStates() {
        List<State> possibleStates = new ArrayList<>();
        List<Move> availableMoves = this.model.getAllPossibleMoves(getIsWhiteTurn(), getBoard());
        availableMoves.forEach(p -> {
            State newState = new State(this.model);
            newState.setIsWhiteTurn(!this.isWhiteTurn);
            newState.getBoard().movePiece(p.getFrom(), p.getTo());
            possibleStates.add(newState);
        });

        return possibleStates;
    }

    void incrementVisit() {
        this.visitCount++;
    }

    void addScore(double score) {
        if (this.winScore != Integer.MIN_VALUE)
            this.winScore += score;
    }
    void randomPlay() {
        List<Move> availableMoves = this.getModel().getAllPossibleMoves(this.getModel().isFirstPlayerTurn(), this.getModel().getChessBoard());
        int totalPossibilities = availableMoves.size();
        int selectRandom = (int) (Math.random() * totalPossibilities);
//        Move move = Collections.max(
//                availableMoves,
//                Comparator.comparing(c -> simulateMove(c,this) ));
        this.model.getChessBoard().movePiece(availableMoves.get(selectRandom).getFrom(), availableMoves.get(selectRandom).getTo());

    }

    void switchPlayer() {
        this.getModel().switchTurn();
    }

    private int calculateMaterialScore(State state) {
        int whiteScore = 0;
        int blackScore = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) {
                Position pos = new Position(i, j);
                Piece piece = state.getBoard().getPieceAt(pos);
                int pieceValue;
                if (piece != null) {
                    pieceValue = piece.getValue();
                    if (piece.getColor().equals(ChessPieceColor.WHITE)) {
                        whiteScore += pieceValue;
                    } else {
                        blackScore += pieceValue;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return whiteScore - blackScore;
    }

column2: Keep JavaFX TreeTableView sorted when Items change
column3:
I have a JavaFX application with a TreeTableView that shows a tree of items that can change in two ways:

  1. Items may be added or removed in the background
  2. The data of the items (shown in the table columns) may change

The TreeTableView, like the TableView, can be sorted either by users clickinig on the column headers or by setting the sort order in the code. This sorting however does not seem to persist when new items are added or when the data changes.

Here is a simple example (tested with OpenJFX 20) that shows my problem. A table is created and also a button for adding random tree elements. Even though the table is supposed to be sorted by the first column, new items always show up on the last row instead of being inserted at their correct location. Only manually re-sorting restores the correct order.

import javafx.application.Application;
import javafx.beans.property.ReadOnlyStringProperty;
import javafx.beans.property.ReadOnlyStringWrapper;
import javafx.scene.Scene;
import javafx.scene.control.*;
import javafx.scene.layout.VBox;
import javafx.stage.Stage;

import java.util.Random;

public class TestApplication extends Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        launch(args);
    }

    @Override
    public void start(Stage primaryStage) {
        TreeTableColumn<Entry, String> columnFirst = new TreeTableColumn<>("First");
        columnFirst.setCellValueFactory(p -> p.getValue().getValue().firstProperty());

        TreeTableColumn<Entry, String> columnSecond = new TreeTableColumn<>("Second");
        columnSecond.setCellValueFactory(p -> p.getValue().getValue().secondProperty());

        TreeTableView<Entry> treeTableView = new TreeTableView<>();
        treeTableView.getColumns().add(columnFirst);
        treeTableView.getColumns().add(columnSecond);

        Button button = new Button("Add Entry");
        button.setOnAction(event -> {
            Random random = new Random();
            String first = String.valueOf((char)(random.nextInt('Z' - 'A') + 'A'));
            String second = String.valueOf((char)(random.nextInt('Z' - 'A') + 'A'));
            Entry entry = new Entry(first, second);

            if(treeTableView.getRoot() == null) {
                treeTableView.setRoot(new TreeItem<>(entry));
                treeTableView.getRoot().setExpanded(true);
                treeTableView.getSortOrder().add(columnFirst);
            }
            else {
                treeTableView.getRoot().getChildren().add(new TreeItem<>(entry));
            }
        });

        VBox vbox = new VBox();
        vbox.getChildren().add(treeTableView);
        vbox.getChildren().add(button);

        Scene scene = new Scene(vbox);
        primaryStage.setScene(scene);
        primaryStage.setTitle("TreeTableView Sorting");
        primaryStage.show();
    }

    public static class Entry {
        private final String first;
        private final String second;

        public Entry(String first, String second) {
            this.first = first;
            this.second = second;
        }

        public ReadOnlyStringProperty firstProperty() {
            return new ReadOnlyStringWrapper(first);
        }

        public ReadOnlyStringProperty secondProperty() {
            return new ReadOnlyStringWrapper(second);
        }
    }
}

For JavaFX's TableView I could achieve a persistent sorting by using a SortedList<T> and binding its comparator to that of the TableView (as suggested in the documentation). Together with setting an extractor to observe changes to the list items themselves this basically solves the problem for the TableView. It just stays sorted in the user-specified way no matter how the data changes.

But I failed to find anything similar for the TreeTableView. The items have an internal observable list that can be accessed with getChildren() but there don't seem to be any customization points here.

Is there an obvious solution to this that I overlooked? Ideally I would like to avoid calling sort() after each change to the backing data.

column2: I'm having trouble understanding Android MasterKeyBuilder and custom aliases
column3:
I am wanting to use a MasterKey to encrypt a file on my Android device, and am a little uncertain on what the correct way is of doing that. The following code works fine across reboots, but I want to make sure the Masterkey won't change on me in the future (For example, after an Android update).

MasterKey masterKey = new MasterKey.Builder(context)
                    .setKeyScheme(MasterKey.KeyScheme.AES256_GCM)
                    .build();
 EncryptedFile encryptedFile = new EncryptedFile.Builder(
                    context,
                    privateKeyFile,
                    masterKey,
                    EncryptedFile.FileEncryptionScheme.AES256_GCM_HKDF_4KB
            ).build();

According to the official docs, the MasterKey.Builder constructor does accept a custom alias, but when I try to do this, I get this exception when trying to build the encryptedFile object.

MasterKey masterKey = new MasterKey.Builder(context,"myAlias")
                    .setKeyScheme(MasterKey.KeyScheme.AES256_GCM)
                    .build();

            // this lets us encrypt the private key file with the master key
            EncryptedFile encryptedFile = new EncryptedFile.Builder(
                    context,
                    privateKeyFile,
                    masterKey,
                    EncryptedFile.FileEncryptionScheme.AES256_GCM_HKDF_4KB
            ).build();

exception: com.google.crypto.tink.shaded.protobuf.InvalidProtocolBufferException: Protocol message contained an invalid tag (zero).

My thinking was if I pass my own alias in, the MasterKey.Builder would use this to always generate the MasterKey the same way, rather than depending on some 'magic' that may or may not change in the future.

According to the answer in this Reddit post, I should be fine, but would be glad if somebody could point me to some more documentation on this.

column2: Cant connect to express server from android app
column3:
I have a backend written with express and an app with Java for android.

Background:

I want to create socket communication between the app and the server, but I can't connect to the server from the app.

The backend side is fully tested, and I can send requests from postman and receive data as well. This is the code inside the server that handles the socket:

import { Server } from "socket.io";
import { SOCKET_EVENTS } from "../../constants/socket.js";
import { getBlockchainBlock } from "../crypto/crypto.js";

const io = new Server(4000, {
  cors: {
    origin: "*",
  },
});

export const openSocket = () => {
  io.on(SOCKET_EVENTS.CONNECTION, async (socket) => {
    console.log("user connected! socket id:", socket.id);

    io.emit(SOCKET_EVENTS.NEW_TASK, {
      data: await getBlockchainBlock(),
    });

    socket.on(SOCKET_EVENTS.TASK_FINISHED, (data) => {
      console.log("User task is done with data:", data);
    });

    socket.on(SOCKET_EVENTS.DISCONNECT, () => {
      console.log("user disconnected! socket id:", socket.id);
    });
  });
};

column2: RestTemplate modifying URL
column3:
Today i have encountered a strange situation: url ending in &timezone=Europe%2FBerlin is modified by Rest template to &timezone=Europe%252FBerlin
Somehow there is 52 added between 2 and %

Here is a brakepoint in debug:

@Nullable
public <T> T execute(String uriTemplate, HttpMethod method, @Nullable RequestCallback requestCallback, @Nullable ResponseExtractor<T> responseExtractor, Object... uriVariables) throws RestClientException {
    URI url = this.getUriTemplateHandler().expand(uriTemplate, uriVariables); // https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?latitude=52.52&longitude=13.41&current_weather=true&hourly=temperature_2m,rain,snowfall,weathercode,surface_pressure,visibility,windspeed_10m,winddirection_10m&daily=temperature_2m_max,temperature_2m_min,sunrise,sunset&start_date=2023-04-01&end_date=2023-04-03&timezone=Europe%252FBerlin
    return this.doExecute(url, uriTemplate, method, requestCallback, responseExtractor);
}

Also screen:

Below is the rest of the code:

import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
public class OpenMeteoService {

    final String baseUrl = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?";

    String setLocalization(Double lat, Double lon) {
        String latValue = lat.toString().replace(",", ".");
        String lonValue = lon.toString().replace(",", ".");
        return String.format("latitude=%s&longitude=%s&current_weather=true", latValue, lonValue);
    }

    String getHourlyForecast(boolean temperature, boolean rain, boolean snowfall, boolean weathercode, boolean pressure, boolean visibility, boolean windSpeed, boolean windDirection) {
        String base = "&hourly=";
        if (temperature) base += "temperature_2m,";
        if (rain) base += "rain,";
        if (snowfall) base += "snowfall,";
        if (weathercode) base += "weathercode,";
        if (pressure) base += "surface_pressure,";
        if (visibility) base += "visibility,";
        if (windSpeed) base += "windspeed_10m,";
        if (windDirection) base += "winddirection_10m,";

        return base.substring(0, base.length() - 1);
    }

    String getDailyWeather(boolean temperatureMax, boolean temperatureMin, boolean sunrise, boolean sunset) {
        ;
        String base = "&daily=";
        if (temperatureMax) base += "temperature_2m_max,";
        if (temperatureMin) base += "temperature_2m_min,";
        if (sunrise) base += "sunrise,";
        if (sunset) base += "sunset,";

        return base.substring(0, base.length() - 1);
    }

    String getDates(String start, String end) {
        return String.format("&start_date=%s&end_date=%s", start, end) + "&timezone=Europe%2FBerlin";
    }

    String getFullUrl(Double lat, Double lon, String start, String end) {
        return baseUrl +
                setLocalization(lat, lon) +
                getHourlyForecast(true, true, true, true, true, true, true, true) +
                getDailyWeather(true, true, true, true) +
                getDates(start, end);
    }

}

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
